ceptions on Collaboration -- t11. The Motivation of Heritage Learners vs. Foreign Language Learners in a University-level Spanish Composition Course -- t12. The Role of Learner Affect in L2 Japanese Writing Tutorials -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost of what we know about writing in a second or foreign language (L2) is based on conclusions drawn from research on L2 writing in English. However, a significant quantity of L2 writing and writing instruction takes place in languages other than English and so there is a need for studies that look beyond English. The chapters in this book focus on languages other than English and investigate curricular issues, multiple languages in contact/conflict in L2 writing instruction and student attitudes toward pedagogical practices. The collection as a whole makes a valuable contribution to the study of L2 writing, and it will also prove an essential resource for instructors of second and foreign language writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aExposition (Rhetoric)xStudy and teaching. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aRhetoricxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisitionxStudy and teaching. 7aREFERENCE / Writing Skills.2bisacsh  aBeyond English.  aL2 Writing.  aNon-English languages.  aRoman Alphabet.  aless-commonly taught languages.  anon-Roman alphabet.  asecond language writing teacher development.  asecond language writing.1 aBorrallo-Solís, Adela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiesa, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuperron, Lucile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFang, Ming, econtributor.4ctb4https:/